<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="509" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1412,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,1412,1437]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Male of 
<taxonomicName box="[388,522,1412,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Aphengium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cupreum">
<emphasis box="[388,522,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">A. cupreum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily distinguishable from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[1008,1138,1412,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Aphengium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1008,1138,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Aphengium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the following character: dorsal surface of head with foveiform punctures separated by distance equivalent to at least two times puncture diameter along most of midline (
<figureCitation box="[661,751,1484,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Fig. 
<number box="[720,751,1484,1509]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, the aedeagus and fronto-lateral peripheral sclerite (FLP) are unique among 
<taxonomicName box="[528,658,1520,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Aphengium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[528,658,1520,1544]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Aphengium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<figureCitation box="[764,860,1519,1544]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1136,1158]" captionTargetBox="[165,1436,193,1114]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[150,1436,193,1115]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 34. Aedeagus of Aphengium; 31. A. sordidum (arrow shows dorsal margin of parameres curved inward at its apical third); 32. A. cupreum; 33. A. ibateguara sp. nov.; 34. A. curtum sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244423/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Figs. 
<number box="[829,860,1520,1544]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="32.38">32</number>
</figureCitation>
, 38). Female can be immediately distinguished by the combination of two characters: punctures on dorsal surface of head usually contiguous (
<figureCitation box="[1202,1288,1556,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Fig. 
<number box="[1256,1288,1556,1581]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
); central and anterior portions of head with rugose surface (
<figureCitation box="[682,767,1591,1616]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Fig. 
<number box="[735,767,1591,1616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="510" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1412,2013]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,1328]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="510" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,340,1628,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Description</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[357,444,1628,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Length</emphasis>
. Small (
<quantity box="[547,646,1628,1652]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7–8 mm</quantity>
) (
<figureCitation box="[673,818,1628,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Figs. 
<number box="[740,818,1628,1652]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="13.14">13, 14</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[841,906,1628,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Head</emphasis>
. Foveiform punctures dense, not contiguous, separated by at least two times puncture diameter (
<figureCitation box="[760,848,1663,1688]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Fig. 
<number box="[817,848,1663,1688]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
); punctures often elliptical. Punctures on anterior portion, near to clypeal teeth, weakly impressed. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[719,842,1700,1725]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Pronotum</emphasis>
. Covered by foveiform, setose punctures; larger on lateral and posterior portions, not contiguous, usually separated by less than one puncture diameter (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1423,1735,1760]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Fig. 
<number box="[1391,1423,1736,1760]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
). Disc of pronotum slightly convex. Anterior angle of pronotum approximately 
<number box="[1076,1109,1772,1796]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="70.0">70</number>
°. Lateral angle greater than 
<number box="[151,184,1808,1832]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="90.0">90</number>
°; margin not explanate. Margin between lateral and posterior angles straight. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1105,1190,1807,1832]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Elytra.</emphasis>
Elongate-oval shape (
<figureCitation box="[159,315,1844,1869]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Figs. 
<number box="[232,315,1844,1868]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="13.14">13, 14</number>
</figureCitation>
). Disc slightly convex, with dense and conspicuous setae. Lateral margins slightly curved outwards. Foveiform punctures separated on the elytral disc by distance equivalent to at least two times puncture diameter. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,620,1916,1941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">Secondary sexual characters.</emphasis>
Besides the sexual dimorphism described for the genus, females differ from males in the following aspects: punctures on dorsal surface of head usually contiguous (
<figureCitation box="[1242,1330,1952,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="509">
Fig. 
<number box="[1298,1330,1952,1977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="509" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Central and anterior portions of head with rugose surface. Punctures on central portion of pronotum small and weakly impressed (
<figureCitation box="[294,389,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,209,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1422,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Aphengium cupreum Shipp; 13. Male (dorsal view); 14. Female (dorsal view); 15. Male head; 16. Female head; 17. Male pronotum; 18. Female pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244420/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="510">
Fig. 
<number box="[358,389,152,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="510" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
); punctures more dispersed than those in males. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1034,1159,151,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="510">Aedeagus.</emphasis>
Length of parameres approximately one-half that of phallobase; ventral margin slightly curved inward; dorsal margin almost straight; apex acuminate (
<figureCitation box="[355,446,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1136,1158]" captionTargetBox="[165,1436,193,1114]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[150,1436,193,1115]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 34. Aedeagus of Aphengium; 31. A. sordidum (arrow shows dorsal margin of parameres curved inward at its apical third); 32. A. cupreum; 33. A. ibateguara sp. nov.; 34. A. curtum sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244423/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="510">
Fig. 
<number box="[413,446,224,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="510" value="32.0">32</number>
</figureCitation>
). Superior right peripheral sclerite (SRP) as in figure 
<number box="[1102,1134,223,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="510" value="36.0">36</number>
. Fronto-lateral peripheral sclerite (FLP) as in figure 
<number box="[453,485,260,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="510" value="38.0">38</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
